Management KVM machines.

1) For bridge interface.

  1.1) Host file /etc/network/interfaces example:
# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system
# and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).

# The loopback network interface
auto lo
iface lo inet loopback

# The primary network interface
auto eth0
iface eth0 inet manual

auto br0
iface br0 inet static
	network 10.0.0.0
	gateway 10.0.0.1
	address 10.0.0.4
	broadcast 10.0.0.255
	netmask 255.255.255.0
	pre-up ifconfig eth0 down
	pre-up brctl addbr br0
	pre-up brctl addif br0 eth0
	pre-up ifconfig br0 up
	pre-up ifconfig eth0 up
	pre-down ifconfig eth0 down
	pre-down ifconfig br0 down
	pre-down brctl delif br0 eth0
	pre-down brctl delbr br0

  1.2) Guest file /etc/network/interfaces example:
# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system
# and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).

# The loopback network interface
auto lo
iface lo inet loopback

# The primary network interface
auto eth0
iface eth0 inet dhcp
